dd531822-5ee5-4961-b9a7-0c38a8115dac.24790ca7-847e-4df9-beab-aed139cecb99.description=
Converts a JSON array or a JSON object to a XML document.

Examples\:
1. json\={ "name"\:"John", "age"\:100, "retired"\:true, "otherInfo"\:null } and the other values with their default values you wil get

  John
  100
  true  

Null values are not converted to XML elements.

2. json\=[{"key"\:"year", "value"\:2013}, {"key"\:"month", "value"\:"11"}] and the other values with their default values you wil get

  year
  2013


  month
  11


Inputs\:
    json - The JSON array or object (in the form of a String).
    prettyPrint - The flag for formatting the resulted XML.
Default value\: true
    showXmlDeclaration - The flag for showing the xml declaration (). If this is true then rootTagName can't be empty. 
Default value\: false
    rootTagName - The XML tag name. If this input is empty you will get a list of XML elements.
    defaultJsonArrayItemName - Default XML tag name for items in a JSON array if there isn't a pair (array name, array item name) defined in jsonArraysNames and jsonArraysItemNames.
Default value\: item
    jsonArraysNames - The list of array names separated by delimiter.
    jsonArraysItemNames - The coresponding list of array item names separated by delimiter.
    namespacesPrefixes - The list of tag prefixes separated by delimiter.
    namespacesUris - The coresponding list of namespaces uris separated by delimiter.
    delimiter - The list separator.
Default value\: ,

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. The resulted XML document or XML elements.
    returnCode - 0 for success; -1 for failure.
	
Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

dd531822-5ee5-4961-b9a7-0c38a8115dac.71cacb84-9633-41ca-b920-0ad5be0febe9.description=
This operation loops as many times as specified in the "count" input, counting from "1" to a greater number, incrementing it by "1" at each iteration.

Inputs\:
    count - The number of loops to complete.
Valid values\: from 1 to 9223372036854775807
    reset - Specifies whether the counter restarts counting from "1".
Valid values\: true, false
Default value\: false
    to - The number to count to. It will take the value of the "count" input field. 
    from - The number to start counting at. For this operation, it is customized to "1".
    incrementBy - The number to increment by while counting. For this operation, it is customized to "1".

Results\:
    resultString – This is the primary output. It contains the value of the number that was just counted.

Responses\:
    has more – The counting process is not complete. One or more iterations are pending.
    no more – The counting process is complete.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
1. It is recommended that you do not change the values of the "to", "from" or "incrementBy" input fields.
2. The "from", "to" and "incrementBy" inputs are customized for this operation. Even though you can also customize them, if you need to specify the loop range borders and the increment value, use the "Counter" operation.

Examples\:
1. For a loop with 20 iterations, the following values should be provided for the input fields\:
    count\: 20
    reset\: false (this field can also be left blank, as "false" is the default value)
2. For an infinite loop, the value of "count" should be at least "1" and the value of "reset" should be "true".

dd531822-5ee5-4961-b9a7-0c38a8115dac.e9c7f29a-d096-4eb9-9d3d-bebe04a5df93.description=
Runs a SQL command against an Oracle database, using the information available in the tnsnames.ora file.   
Does not return any results (only whether the command was executed)

Input Parameters\:
TNSPath - The path to the parent folder of the TNS file which contains the DB connecting info(the name of the DB server, the port used for connecting to the DB server, the database name)
TNSEntry - the entry name from the tnsnames.ora file which contains the connecting information
Username - username to connect as
Password - password
Command - the command to execute

Responses\:
more items - the command was executed successfully
failure - the command could not be executed

Extra Results\:
updateCount - the update count of the command executed

NOTE\: 
This op supports only Oracle. The tnsnames.ora file should correctly configured on the RAS machine.

ORACLE NOTE\:
It is possible to run PL/SQL procedures using this operation. The examples below present the syntax to be used for having the same effect as the following PL/SQL script\:
BEGIN
  send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');
END;

Example 1\: BEGIN send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test');END;

Example 2\: BEGIN send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test');END;

Example 3\: {CALL send_message(addressee\=>'b@hp.com',sender\=>'pas@hp.com',subject\=>'Test',message\=>'Test')}

Example 4\: {CALL send_message('b@hp.com','pas@hp.com','Test','Test')}
